tic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration between memory-pressure signal, threshold config, and strategy selector. Unit tests on selector logic alone can miss state handoff/wiring bugs. Rejected System because the behavior text does not explicitly require real OS memory telemetry or external response-contract validation; the threshold crossing can be simulated in-process.","test_description":"Create an integration test with real cache modules wired together: set threshold/config, drive memory-usage metric below/above threshold, and assert active strategy changes from LRU to LFU at the boundary and remains stable when toggling around it.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This behavior explicitly depends on real external infrastructure (PostgreSQL) and proving an externally visible side effect via round trip (DB write -> cache invalidated/read misses). Unit/integration fakes can hide real invalidation timing/transaction/notification issues. SYSTEM TRIAD trigger applies via explicit round-trip side-effect verification.","test_description":"Run against a real PostgreSQL instance: prime cache for rows, perform actual table write/update/delete, then read through application path and verify affected keys are invalidated (miss/refetch) while unaffected keys remain valid.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5